entries.meaning: An aquatic blood-sucking annelid of class Hirudinea, especially Hirudo medicinalis.
examples: The leech on his leg had swelled to more than five inches long, puffed and swollen on his blood.

entries.meaning: (figuratively) A person who derives profit from others in a parasitic fashion.
examples: 'Wrecked his body and his mind, no use to hisself or his family or nobody, just a leech on society'.

entries.meaning: (medicine, dated) A glass tube designed for drawing blood from damaged tissue by means of a vacuum.

verbs.description: leech (third-person singular simple present leeches, present participle leeching, simple past and past participle leeched)

entries.meaning: (transitive, literally) To apply a leech medicinally, so that it sucks blood from the patient.
examples: The poppy made him sleep and while he slept they leeched him to drain off the bad blood.

entries.meaning: (transitive, figuratively) To drain (resources) without giving back.
examples: Bert leeched hundreds of files from the BBS, but never uploaded anything in return.

entries.meaning: (nautical) The vertical edge of a square sail.
examples: To help combat these problems, almost all sailmakers trim the leeches of their headsails to a hollow or concave profile and enclose a LEECHLINE within the leech tabling.

entries.meaning: (nautical) The aft edge of a triangular sail.
examples: Trim the leech of the jib parallel to the main by watching the slot between the mainsail and the jib.
